Canada’s middle class was substantially lagging behind the U.S. back in 2000, but it caught up in 2010 and has since surpassed the U.S.

In Western Europe, the average incomes still trail those the United States, but the gap in several countires such as Britain, the Netherlands and Sweden is much smaller than it was a decade ago. 

The income data were compiled by researcher from the LIS who analyzed date from the Luxembourg Income Study database in connection with The New York Times.

If the middle class are having a bad time, then the poor in the United States have it even worse.

