Yet according to one of the most commonly cited economic statistics - per capita gross domestic product - the U.S. continues to maintain its lead as the world’s richest large country.

Most Americans aren't keeping pace with their counterparts around the world because a large share of recent income gains is flowing to a small slice of high-earning households.

‘The idea that the median American has so much more income than the middle class in all other parts of the world is not true these days,’ Harvard economist Lawrence Katz told the Times.

‘In 1960, we were massively richer than anyone else. In 1980, we were richer. In the 1990s, we were still richer.’

That is no longer the case, he added.

